by /DC=com/DC=DigiCert-Grid/O=Open Science Grid/OU=People/CN=Michael Timony 888</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23482#1418674261'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-15T20:11:01+00:00">Dec 15, 2014 08:11 PM UTC</time> by <b>Tim Cartwright</b><a class="anchor" name="1418674261">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Mick&#58;

Thanks for the detailed and helpful background! Very good to know.

I think that EL 6 deprecation and end of support is a LONG way off. We have not yet deprecated EL 5! While I totally understand about minimizing effort, I think you are safe with EL 6 as your foundation for quite a while, especially if you want to get these machines up reasonably soon with production-ready packages. At very least, I agree with your proposal to start with CentOS 6 and maybe, if you can wait a while and/or take on extra risk (which could result in extra effort…), test EL 7 support on the second machine. Again, much depends on your timelines, though.

If you have further questions, I would be happy to try to address them. Otherwise, it seems like your original question has been answered, in which case we can close this ticket?

— Tim</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23482#1418672148'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-15T19:35:48+00:00">Dec 15, 2014 07:35 PM UTC</time><a class="anchor" name="1418672148">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Tim,

The SBGrid is setting up a replacement Glidein server and using Centos 7 would make future upgrades easier and involve less time spend on maintenance. See below for more details&#58;

Currently we have two Glidein servers&#58;

* glidein.nebiogrid.org (Primary)
* glidein-1.sbgrid.org   (Backup)

glidein is our primary and is running Centos 5 and Pacman packages. We&#39;ve never used glidein-1 as it crashes under load and we&#39;re replacing it with a new server that will eventually become our primary server and will also be named glidein-1.sbgrid.org.

The new server is a clean slate and using Centos 7 would require us to perform less maintenance as we wouldn&#39;t have to worry about EOL for Centos 6. Anything I can do to ensure we can get the maximum life out of a server with the minimum of maintenance is a win for us as we&#39;re always suffering from a time-crunch and don&#39;t have often much time to spend on upgrading server OS&#39;s etc.

Once glidein-1 is working, we will decommission our primary Glidein server and repurposed it as a backup Glidein server to be known as glidein-2.sbgrid.org

What we can do is use Centos 6, and when we start work on glidein-2 we can test Centos 7 on it for you?

Does that answer your question? And I can&#39;t wait to get our Glidein servers on RPM based packages! &#58;)

Cheers
Mick

by /DC=com/DC=DigiCert-Grid/O=Open Science Grid/OU=People/CN=Michael Timony 888</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23482#1418396615'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-12T15:03:35+00:00">Dec 12, 2014 03:03 PM UTC</time> by <b>Tim Cartwright</b><a class="anchor" name="1418396615">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hi Mick. We are indeed working on EL 7 support. It is a bit slow going, especially with our Java components, but we are making good progress on the Worker Node Client packages. As for an official release, that is a bit hard to predict at the moment. We might put something out there in a limited fashion within the next few months, or even just make our testing repository available. Lots of options for less-than-100%-official releases. But if I had to bet, I would say that we will wait for an official release of EL 7 (which may be incomplete at first) in OSG 3.3, which will come no earlier than May.

Let me turn the question around ... what systems do you want to move to EL 7, when, and why? The more we know about our community and their motivations, the better our planning can be.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23482#1418327888'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-11T19:58:08+00:00">Dec 11, 2014 07:58 PM UTC</time> by <b>Tim Theisen</b><a class="anchor" name="1418327888">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Tim Cartwright is probably best able to address this question.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23482#1418326632'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-11T19:37:12+00:00">Dec 11, 2014 07:37 PM UTC</time> by <b>OSG-GOC</b><a class="anchor" name="1418326632">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Is there a timeline for RHEL/Centos/SC 7 OS support?

